  Here's the architecture I'm planning so you can validate before we write a line:
                                                                                                                                    
  Two targets in one Xcode project:
                                                                                                                                    
  ┌───────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐         
  │      Target       │                                               Role                                                │         
  ├───────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤         
  │ ClipboardDaemon   │ Background agent (LSUIElement), no dock/menu bar. Monitors clipboard, handles hotkey, shows panel │
  ├───────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ ClipboardSettings │ Normal app, only open when configuring. Reads/writes shared config                                │         
  └───────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘         
                                                                                                                                    
  Shared config via an App Group UserDefaults (both targets share the same suite).                                                  
                  
  Panel — NSPanel with .nonactivatingPanel behavior so it doesn't steal focus. Keyboard navigation + click. Dismisses on selection  
  or Escape.      
                                                                                                                                    
  Paste flow — record frontmost app before panel opens → user selects → simulate Cmd+V into that app via CGEvent → item moves to top
   of history.
                                                                                                                                    
  Clipboard polling — check NSPasteboard.changeCount every 0.5s, capture on change if source app isn't excluded.                    
  
  Permissions required — Accessibility (for simulating paste) and optionally Screen Recording (to detect source app name — actually 
  just NSWorkspace is enough for bundle ID, so no extra permission needed).
                                                                                                                                    
  Does this match your vision?
  Yes, screen recording shouldn't be needed. I can try and pull inspiration from a different app in how they manage that.
